      {
        "subtopic": "Definition",
        "content": "Compound Interest (CI) is the interest calculated on the initial principal and also on the accumulated interest of previous periods. It results in 'interest on interest' and is commonly used in financial calculations like loans, investments, and bank accounts."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "topic": "Compound Interest Formula",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "Standard Formula",
        "content": "CI = P × (1 + R/100)^T − P\nWhere:\nP = Principal\nR = Rate of Interest per annum\nT = Time (in years)\nCI = Compound Interest"
      },
      {
        "subtopic": "Example 1",
        "content": "**Q:** Find CI on ₹5000 at 10% p.a. for 2 years.\n**Solution:**\nCI = 5000 × (1 + 10/100)^2 − 5000 = 5000 × (1.1)^2 − 5000 = 5000 × 1.21 − 5000 = ₹6050 − ₹5000 = ₹1050\n**Answer:** ₹1050"
      },
      {
        "subtopic": "Example 2",
        "content": "**Q:** Find the compound interest on ₹8000 at 5% p.a. for 3 years.\n**Solution:**\nCI = 8000 × (1 + 5/100)^3 − 8000 = 8000 × (1.157625) − 8000 = ₹9261 − ₹8000 = ₹1261\n**Answer:** ₹1261"
      }
    ]
  },
